paragraphs.text:
%md
## Single view demo

#### Goal

Demonstrate how [Apache Hive](http://hortonworks.com/hadoop/hive/) on [HDP Sandbox](http://hortonworks.com/sandbox) can help retailer get a single view of a product by combining data from different sources and run interative queries against the data. In this case, the data sources are:
  - ETL/CRM data from EDW/DB - ingested using [Apache Sqoop](http://hortonworks.com/hadoop/sqoop/)
  - Web traffic data - ingested using [HDF](http://hortonworks.com/hdf)
  - Social media data - ingested using [HDF](http://hortonworks.com/hdf)
  
#### Steps

0. Pre-reqs: Setup and import retail data set into DB/EDW (in this case: Postgres)
1. Use Sqoop to import CRM/ERP data from DB/EDW into Hive
2. Use HDF to import related tweets into Hive
3. Use HDF to import simulated web traffic logs into Hive
4. Use Hive to analyze tables to populate statistics
5. Use Hive to correlate the data from multiple data sources

Note: this is a simplified version of the demo. A more realistic self-lab of this content is available that:
  - runs the steps as either IT user (for setup) or marketing user (as business user running queries)
  - uses Ranger to setup authorization policies and audit


More details available at [https://github.com/abajwa-hw/single-view-demo](https://github.com/abajwa-hw/single-view-demo)

paragraphs.text:
%md
#### 1. Pre-requisites
Before running this notebook:
1. *Not required on HDP Sandbox as it already has these set*
Enable [Hive transactions](https://cwiki.apache.org/confluence/display/Hive/Hive+Transactions) by setting below via Ambari > Hive > Config:
```
hive.support.concurrency = true
hive.enforce.bucketing = true 
hive.exec.dynamic.partition.mode = nonstrict
hive.txn.manager = org.apache.hadoop.hive.ql.lockmgr.DbTxnManager
hive.compactor.initiator.on = true
```
2. Run below as root to give zeppelin sudo priviledge
```
echo "zeppelin  ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD: ALL" >> /etc/sudoers
```
3. Run below to enable zeppelin to log in to postgres
```
echo "host all all 127.0.0.1/32 md5" >> /var/lib/pgsql/data/pg_hba.conf
```

paragraphs.title: Restart postgres
paragraphs.text:
%sh
# on sandbox, use 'service ambari stop/start'
# on cluster, use 'service ambari-server stop/start'
count=$(chkconfig --list | grep ambari | wc -l)
if [ $count -eq 3 ]
then
    ambari_svc="ambari" 
else
    ambari_svc="ambari-server"
fi

sudo service $ambari_svc stop
sudo service postgresql stop
sudo service postgresql start
sudo service $ambari_svc start

paragraphs.text:
%md

#### Incremental import of data into Hive from RDBMS

Now that we did the one time bulk import, next we will setup an incremental sqoop job

First we create password file containing zeppelin user's PostGres password in HDFS. This is done to allow invocations of the job to be automated/scheduled (without having to manually pass the password )

result.msg:
Incremental import of data into Hive from RDBMS

Now that we did the one time bulk import, next we will setup an incremental sqoop job

First we create password file containing zeppelin user's PostGres password in HDFS. This is done to allow invocations of the job to be automated/scheduled (without having to manually pass the password )

paragraphs.text:
%sh
# use -n to ensure newline is not added
echo -n "zeppelin" > .password
hadoop fs -put .password /user/zeppelin/
rm .password

%md
Create incremental import sqoop job for factsales table and point it as below: 
  - --table: table the job is for (i.e. factsales)
  - --password-file: the HDFS location of the password file
  - --incremental: lastmodified (we want to use lastmodified logic to find delta records)
  - --check-column: specify which column that will be used to determine which delta records will be picked up (in this case, records whose updatedate column value is later than 2015-01-01 will be picked up)
  - see [Sqoop documentation on incremental imports](https://sqoop.apache.org/docs/1.4.2/SqoopUserGuide.html#_incremental_imports) for more details

result.msg:
Create incremental import sqoop job for factsales table and point it as below:

  • –table: table the job is for (i.e. factsales)
  • –password-file: the HDFS location of the password file
  • –incremental: lastmodified (we want to use lastmodified logic to find delta records)
  • –check-column: specify which column that will be used to determine which delta records will be picked up (in this case, records whose updatedate column value is later than 2015-01-01 will be picked up)
  • see Sqoop documentation on incremental imports for more details

paragraphs.title: Create incremental sqoop job
paragraphs.text:
%sh
sqoop job -create factsales -- import --verbose --connect 'jdbc:postgresql://localhost:5432/contoso' --table factsales -username zeppelin --password-file hdfs://sandbox.hortonworks.com:8020/user/zeppelin/.password --check-column updatedate --incremental lastmodified --last-value '2015-01-01' --hive-import  --direct

paragraphs.title: Update 2 records of FactSales table (in Postgres)
paragraphs.text:
%sh
export PGPASSWORD=zeppelin
psql -U zeppelin -d contoso -h localhost -c "update factsales set updatedate = '2016-01-01 00:00:00' where saleskey in (1,2);"

result.msg: UPDATE 2

paragraphs.title: Empty the staging table in hive
paragraphs.text:
%hive
truncate table factsales

result.msg: The query did not generate a result set!

paragraphs.title: Execute incremental sqoop job
paragraphs.text:
%sh



#Copies Records Modified In PostGres To Hive

sqoop job -exec factsales

paragraphs.text:
%md
#### Step 3. and 4.: Ingest product-related tweets and weblogs into HDFS via Nifi

a) Follow steps below to install Nifi via Ambari, monitor certain tweets and push to HDFS, Hive and Solr:

- Download Nifi Ambari service folder
```
VERSION=`hdp-select status hadoop-client | sed 's/hadoop-client - \([0-9]\.[0-9]\).*/\1/'`
sudo git clone https://github.com/abajwa-hw/ambari-nifi-service.git   /var/lib/ambari-server/resources/stacks/HDP/$VERSION/services/NIFI   
sudo service ambari restart
```
- To install Nifi, start the 'Install Wizard': Open Ambari (http://sandbox.hortonworks.com:8080) then:
On bottom left -> Actions -> Add service -> check NiFi server -> Next -> Next -> Change any config you like (e.g. install dir, port, setup_prebuilt or values in nifi.properties) -> Next -> Deploy. This will kick off the install which will run for 5-10min.

- Now open Nifi webui (http://sandbox.hortonworks.com:9090)
- Download prebuilt Single_view_demo.xml template to your laptop from [here](https://github.com/abajwa-hw/single-view-demo/raw/master/template/Single_view_demo.xml)
- Import the Single_view_demo.xml template info Nifi
- Fill out env specific configs e.g. your Twitter credentials (see note below)
- Do not start the flows yet


b) More detailed instructions on how to install Nifi on sandbox and import a template flow to ingest tweets available at [https://community.hortonworks.com/articles/1282/sample-hdfnifi-flow-to-push-tweets-into-solrbanana.html](https://community.hortonworks.com/articles/1282/sample-hdfnifi-flow-to-push-tweets-into-solrbanana.html)

c) Note that to monitor tweets, Twitter requires you to have an account and obtain developer keys by registering an "app". Follow steps below to do this:
- Create a Twitter account and app and get your consumer key/token and access keys/tokens:
  - Open https://apps.twitter.com 
  - sign in
  - create new app
  - fill anything
  - create access tokens

result.msg:
Step 3. and 4.: Ingest product-related tweets and weblogs into HDFS via Nifi

a) Follow steps below to install Nifi via Ambari, monitor certain tweets and push to HDFS, Hive and Solr:

  • Download Nifi Ambari service folder

    VERSION=`hdp-select status hadoop-client | sed 's/hadoop-client - \([0-9]\.[0-9]\).*/\1/'`
sudo git clone https://github.com/abajwa-hw/ambari-nifi-service.git   /var/lib/ambari-server/resources/stacks/HDP/$VERSION/services/NIFI   
sudo service ambari restart

  • To install Nifi, start the 'Install Wizard': Open Ambari (http://sandbox.hortonworks.com:8080) then:
    On bottom left -> Actions -> Add service -> check NiFi server -> Next -> Next -> Change any config you like (e.g. install dir, port, setup_prebuilt or values in nifi.properties) -> Next -> Deploy. This will kick off the install which will run for 5-10min.

  • Now open Nifi webui (http://sandbox.hortonworks.com:9090)

  • Download prebuilt Single_view_demo.xml template to your laptop from here

  • Import the Single_view_demo.xml template info Nifi

  • Fill out env specific configs e.g. your Twitter credentials (see note below)

  • Do not start the flows yet

b) More detailed instructions on how to install Nifi on sandbox and import a template flow to ingest tweets available at https://community.hortonworks.com/articles/1282/sample-hdfnifi-flow-to-push-tweets-into-solrbanana.html

c) Note that to monitor tweets, Twitter requires you to have an account and obtain developer keys by registering an “app”. Follow steps below to do this:

  • Create a Twitter account and app and get your consumer key/token and access keys/tokens:
  • Open https://apps.twitter.com
  • sign in
  • create new app
  • fill anything
  • create access tokens

paragraphs.title: Create script to Generate weblog. Copy to a dir accessible by nifi
paragraphs.text:
%sh
cp /home/zeppelin/single-view-demo/createlog-psql.sh /tmp
cp /home/zeppelin/single-view-demo/DimCustomer.csv /tmp

echo "/tmp/createlog-psql.sh /tmp/data/DimCustomer.csv 20 >> /tmp/webtraffic.log" >> /tmp/generate-weblog.sh

chmod 777 /tmp/createlog-psql.sh
chmod 777 /tmp/generate-weblog.sh
chmod 444 /tmp/DimCustomer.csv

paragraphs.text:
%hive
select product,year_visited, sum(time_spent) as total_time from
(select table1.product,year(visited) as year_visited, 
month(visited) as month,unix_timestamp(table1.lead_window_0) - unix_timestamp(table1.visited) as time_spent
from (select product,visited,lead(visited)  over (PARTITION BY session ORDER BY visited asc) from weblog) table1 
where table1.lead_window_0 is not NULL) table2
group by product,year_visited 
order by total_time desc limit 100

#### Conclusion

This concludes the demo. We have shown how you can use Hive to get a single view of product by combining: 
  - ETL/CRM data from EDW/DB (ingested using Sqoop)
  - web traffic  (ingested using HDF)
  - social media data (ingested using HDF)
